I learned the hard way that modifying Swing components outside of the AWT thread causes things to randomly break. Namely, I had an issue where I was modifying a tree model in a multithreaded application and it was breaking the iterators used by the AWT thread to render the tree. My solution was to use [`SwingUtilities#invokeAndWait(Runnable)`][1] within a synchronized method in order to manipulate the tree model, and to call this method from my multiple threads. Here&#39;s an example:

	public static synchronized void addNodeThreadSafe(JTree tree, MutableTreeNode node) {
		Runnable runnable = () -&gt; {
			DefaultTreeModel model = (DefaultTreeModel) tree.getModel();
			MutableTreeNode root = (MutableTreeNode) model.getRoot();

			model.insertNodeInto(node, root, root.getChildCount() - 1);
			model.reload(root);
		};

		if (EventQueue.isDispatchThread()) {
			runnable.run();
		} else {
			try {
				SwingUtilities.invokeAndWait(runnable);
			} catch (InvocationTargetException | InterruptedException e) {
				// Handle exception
			}
		}
	}


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/javax/swing/SwingUtilities.html#invokeAndWait-java.lang.Runnable-

