`exceptionally` must return the same type as the original future. Since the generic type of your return type is `Collection&lt;String&gt;`, you must help the Java compiler figure out that your future really returns a `Collection` and not a `List`.

All options to fix this issue are trivial: type witness, cast, or temporary variable.

Type witness:

	CompletionStage&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt; fn1(String prefix) {
		return fn2()
				.&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt;thenApply(list -&gt; list.stream()
						.map(s -&gt; prefix + s)
						.collect(Collectors.toList())
				).exceptionally(t -&gt; Collections.emptyList());
	}

Cast:

	CompletionStage&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt; fn1(String prefix) {
		return fn2()
				.thenApply(list -&gt; (Collection&lt;String&gt;)list.stream()
						.map(s -&gt; prefix + s)
						.collect(Collectors.toList())
				).exceptionally(t -&gt; Collections.emptyList());
	}

Variable:

	CompletionStage&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt; fn1(String prefix) {
		final CompletionStage&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt; stage = fn2()
				.thenApply(list -&gt; list.stream()
						.map(s -&gt; prefix + s)
						.collect(Collectors.toList()));
		return stage.exceptionally(t -&gt; Collections.emptyList());
	}

I can provide a few more options to the answer from @knittl :

The compiler doesn&#39;t assume that a `CompletionStage&lt;List&lt;String&gt;&gt;` is  &quot;similar enough&quot; to a `CompletionStage&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt;`, so you cannot return the form with the `List` type parameter in place of the form with the `Collection` type parameter.

If you would be able to change the signature of `fn1` in this way, your problem would have been gone:

```
CompletionStage&lt;? extends Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt; fn1(String prefix) {
  return fn2()
      .thenApply(list1 -&gt; list1.stream()
          .map(s1 -&gt; prefix + s1)
          .collect(Collectors.toList()))
      .exceptionally(t -&gt; List.of());
}
```

In that case you would not even need the mapping you do inside the `thenApply` right now, if you do it mainly for the type conversion.

Or if your exception handling is not for the mapping but for the call to `fn2()`, you could simply flip the exception handling and the mapping in order:
```
CompletionStage&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt; fn1(String prefix) {
  return fn2()
      .exceptionally(t -&gt; List.of())
      .thenApply(list -&gt; list.stream()
          .map(s -&gt; prefix + s)
          .collect(Collectors.toList())
      );
}
```

Or if you need that mapping and the exception handling in that order, you could apply another &quot;mapping&quot; at the end:

```
CompletionStage&lt;Collection&lt;String&gt;&gt; fn1(String prefix) {
  return fn2()
      .thenApply(list1 -&gt; list1.stream()
          .map(s1 -&gt; prefix + s1)
          .collect(Collectors.toList()))
      .exceptionally(t -&gt; List.of())
      .thenApply(Function.identity());
}
```
(In this case the second &quot;mapping&quot; really doesn&#39;t do much except convince the compiler to accept a `List&lt;String&gt;` as a `Collection&lt;String&gt;` by another call to a standard function that returns it&#39;s input without further processing.)

